---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="China Discovery Hub is a curated, open-source directory built to give the world a calmer doorway into Chinese language, culture and life."
>
  <article class="container-page py-16 max-w-prose">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-accent">About</p>
    <h1 class="mt-3 font-serif text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
      A calmer doorway into China.
    </h1>

    <div class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-headings:font-serif prose-headings:tracking-tight max-w-none mt-10">
      <p>
        In January 2025, hundreds of thousands of "TikTok refugees" landed on
        Xiaohongshu (RedNote). For the first time, ordinary internet users
        from outside China sat in the same comment threads as ordinary internet
        users inside it — exchanging pet photos, recipe questions, study tips,
        and "what's it like over there?" stories. The world's curiosity about
        China is back, in a more humane shape than the cable-news version.
      </p>

      <p>
        But the resources to actually <em>satisfy</em> that curiosity are
        scattered. A great Cantonese cooking channel here. A grammar wiki
        there. A long-form China podcast somewhere on a forum. Wikipedia
        articles that assume you already know things. Reddit threads that get
        buried.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>China Discovery Hub</strong> is a single, calm directory of
        the resources we'd actually hand a curious friend. Hand-picked by
        editors. Open to community submissions. No tracking, no algorithm.
      </p>

      <h2>What we curate</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Language</strong> — apps, dictionaries, courses, listening practice.</li>
        <li><strong>Culture & history</strong> — primary sources, podcasts, accessible scholarship.</li>
        <li><strong>Food</strong> — real regional cuisines, recipe channels, sourcing.</li>
        <li><strong>Travel</strong> — visas, transport, city guides, payment apps for tourists.</li>
        <li><strong>Living in China</strong> — visas, banking, healthcare, expat communities.</li>
        <li><strong>Apps & platforms</strong> — how the Chinese internet actually works.</li>
        <li><strong>Entertainment</strong> — C-dramas, films, music, donghua animation.</li>
        <li><strong>Business & tech</strong> — leading companies, AI, EVs, cross-border.</li>
        <li><strong>Media & news</strong> — diverse English-language perspectives.</li>
        <li><strong>Diaspora</strong> — Chinese cultures, far from home.</li>
        <li><strong>Subcultures</strong> — Hanfu, guochao, citywalk, ACG, esports.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Editorial principles</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Cultural first, political second.</strong> We don't take
          sides on geopolitics. We <em>do</em> share resources from across the
          spectrum so readers can triangulate.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Quality before quantity.</strong> Every entry needs to be
          something a friend would actually thank you for sending. Broken
          links, dead projects and pure aggregators get cut.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Accessible to outsiders.</strong> If a resource requires
          fluent Mandarin or a Chinese mobile number to use, we flag that
          clearly so readers know what they're getting into.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No paid placement.</strong> Featured slots are editorial
          choices, not advertisements. If that ever changes, it will be
          labeled prominently and there will be a public ledger.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Open source.</strong> The site, its content, and its build
          process are all public on GitHub.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Who's behind this</h2>
      <p>
        A small group of contributors who all spent time learning Mandarin,
        living in or visiting China, working with Chinese teams, or just
        loving the food too much. We're building this in the open as a public
        good — if it earns coffee money via newsletter sponsorships someday,
        great; if not, it's still worth doing.
      </p>

      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Send corrections, recommendations or partnership ideas via the
        <a href="/submit">submit form</a>, the GitHub repo, or open an issue
        on any specific resource.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
